{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Productcodes}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Productcodes}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 1.14.\tab Product codes
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {received on account}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 ProffittCenter makes use of a number of special codes, or numbers, to implement functions such as \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul received on account\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  or \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul own use\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 . A consequence of this is that these numbers may not be used for products. This is no problem if product Bar codes are used, as all legal EAN or UPC Bar codes are acceptable; but it does need to be considered if product codes are created for your own use.
\par Small numbers, up to 129,999 are interpreted as a cash tender (i.e. \'a31299.99), so these numbers may not be used. 
\par Ten digit numbers that begin with \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 1000030 to 1000039 are used internally and should not be allocated as product codes. To allow for some further extensions, this range of restricted numbers should be extended to a maximum of 1000399999.\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par The numbers \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 1000001 to 1000026 are interpreted as \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul hot key\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 s, product codes generated by pressing a single character on the keyboard. These are legal codes, but you should be aware of their interpretation.
\par See the section on \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul 10000 codes\plain\f8\fs24\cf0  for details of invented bar code for internal use.\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_updatingtheprogram}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_updatingtheprogram}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 1.15.\tab Updating the program
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 ProffittCenter is open source which has the particular advantage that program updates never add to the cost of ownership. This means that you benefit from the constantly improving program and its developments. Installing the latest version will have no effect on the database, which is a separate program (MySQL).  Just download the latest version periodically, and then install as you did the first time around. There is no need to uninstall before doing this. The 'jasper' files located in ProffittCenterReports are not overwritten. This is so that you can modify these files using the open source iReport program, and your modifications will not be overwritten. You might need to do this to get a different layout of invoices. If on the other hand, you find one of the reports lacking, just delete the particular jasper files and on install, they will be replaced by the latest version.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 2.\tab Quick start
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_firststeps}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_firststeps}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.1.\tab First steps
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Many users are somewhat daunted by the size of the help files, so the following pages have been added so that an initial sale can be completed with little or no prior knowledge. Once you have followed these simple steps a few times, you will be able to dip into the help files with other, more complex issues, such as deliveries, orders, accounts, etc.
\par Before starting you need to install \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul XAMPP\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 . If you have not done this already, download XAMPP via the Internet from the Apache Friends website. Make sure that MySQL and Apache are running as a service by looking at the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul XAMPP\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  control panel. Start these services, and ensure that they start on startup, if they are not currently running.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_xampp}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_xampp}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.2.\tab XAMPP
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 XAMPP is a combined package for installing MySQL, the Apache web server, and certain other useful programs. Download the package from the Apache Friends website at http://www.apachefriends.org/en/xampp.html, and chose the XAMPP for Windows package. Install this and select the option Install as a service when asked.
\par The first time you start ProffittCenter Pro, you will be presented with the Settings screen. Enter the desired fields for user name and password and then click the Test button on the lower left.{\field{\*\fldinst{INCLUDEPICTURE "Test button.bmp" MERGEFORMAT}}} If the MySQL database is available, the Create database button will be enabled, but if not, a warning message will be given. The most probable reason would be that the MySQL database is not running, so start the XAMPP Control Panel:
\par {\field{\*\fldinst{INCLUDEPICTURE "XAMPP Control.bmp" MERGEFORMAT}}}
\par Click the two Svc boxes for Apache and MySQL and then click the adjacent Start buttons, and then, when the two services are running successfully, close the control panel, and try ProffittCenter Pro again.
\par Then click the Create database button. The Create tables button will be enabled. Click this, and after a further delay, the OK button will be enabled. Click this to start.
\par You can go back later and enter other values into the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Settings\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Yourfirstsale}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Yourfirstsale}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.3.\tab Your first sale
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {ProffittCenter}}}{\v{\xe {EPOS}}}{\v{\xe {unrecognised product}}}{\v{\xe {import table}}}{\v{\xe {hotkey}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 Log in by typing 10000370000 followed by the Enter key when the program starts. (Conveniently, this number is already sitting there, ready for you to just press the Enter key.) This will log you in as the default operator. Then press the letter 'i' followed by the Enter key. The letter i is a \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul hotkey\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 . The system will issue an error beep for an unrecognised product. Repeat pressing the letter i followed by the enter key a second time. This time, the wording next to the data entry box changes to 'Enter a description...'. By forcing the operator to enter a code twice, ProffittCenter avoids the creation of a new product when a bar code is only partially read or miss-read. Type in a description of the product you want associated with the letter i, for example 'ice pole', and press the Tab key. Descriptions are automatically capitalised, so that 'ice pole' becomes 'Ice Pole'. The caption changes to 'Enter price in pence ..'. As a general rule, all prices are entered in pence (or your local smallest currency unit, such as cents), just as they would be on a cash register.
\par Now, after pressing the Tab or Enter key again, the first ever item will be shown as sold on the screen, and a sales total will be shown on the right.
\par \plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Sellingmorethanone}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Sellingmorethanone}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.4.\tab Selling more than one
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 Now, let us increase the number of items sold from one to five. Type *5 followed by enter, just as you might on a calculator. The number sold will increase to five. (Note, that this is not really like a calculator as if we follow this action by typing *4, the quantity will become 4 and not 20) You can also increase this by one more just by pressing the Enter key; the quantity will increase by one each time you do this, just like on your present cash register. You could also combine two steps into one by typing i5  followed by the Tab key, to save time.
\par Additional products can also be sold. Try typing p20 for 20p worth of penny sweets, and follow the same steps to create a new product as before.
\par 
\par \plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_PayingForIt}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_PayingForIt}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.5.\tab Paying for it
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {cheque}}}{\v{\xe {coupons}}}{\v{\xe {credit card}}}{\v{\xe {debit card}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 Now to accept payment! Assume that the customer offers one pound in payment. Type 100 followed by Tab key. Money values are always entered in pence, with ProffittCenter. The money is accepted, and the change calculated. Your first sale is completed.
\par You will also be able to accept full or partial payment by \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul credit or debit card\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 , or with money off \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul coupons\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 .
\par 
\par \plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Makingaproductpermanent}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Makingaproductpermanent}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.6.\tab Making a product permanent
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 When we entered new products in the sales screen, we created a temporary product, saving time when a customer is waiting. After your first rush of sales, it is time to make this temporary product into a more permanent one. Temporary products are just products that are assigned to the temporary, default department.
\par To convert this temporary product to a permanent one, click on the menu selection, Stock|Temp stock.
\par The first temporary product is shown.
\par Using the mouse, drop down the department combo box and select a department. There are no departments at present other than the Default one for temporary products. This time we first need to create a department for our new product. Press the Escape key to clear the screen and the select Tables|Departments for a list of available departments. Click the New button and fill in the details, tabbing between fields. Leave the default minimum at 0. Create an entry for a department to hold Ice Cream products, with Standard Rate Tax. When you are done, click the OK button. Press the Escape key to clear the Departments screen, as before.
\par Now go back to Temp Stock., and this time, select this new department for Ice Poles, leaving the SKU (Stock Keeping Unit) entry blank. The new SKU screen is displayed. There can be more than one product linked to the same SKU.
\par Entries for the new stock dialog have been filled in from the defaults for the department chosen. The stock quantity is zero, but this can be changed if you wish to reflect the true stock level.
\par The default settings for the ice cream department are for standard rate items (UK). If we need to change the VAT, use the drop down box. When this has been done, click the OK button with the mouse, or simply use the Tab key to step to the OK button and then press the Enter key. Then press the Enter key again to accept the remaining product screen. If there are any more temporary products, these will appear, one by one.\plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Goingfurther}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Goingfurther}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 2.7.\tab Going further
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 Now that we have rushed through a sale or two - feel free to do more, or add further products either using different hot keys or typing or scanning in the full bar code for any available product - it is time to explore the system a bit more. 
\par Try deleting a product sale before it has been paid for: just press the delete key if it is the last item sold, or if not, select the desired line with your mouse before pressing delete.
\par Select the menu item Tables, and then choose Products to see the stored products so far. 
\par Now press the escape key to dismiss this form, and select the Tables|Sales|All menu selection, to examine past sales.
\par Now try a stock take screen, say the menu selection Stock|Stock take|All, and you will see a list of products needing a stock checked. Any items entered today will not appear, as it assumed that the correct stock level was entered when you created the product entry. The stock level for any item can be amended by double clicking on the stock quantity column, and over typing.
\par Feel free to examine further aspects of the system. Try selecting Reports|Takings and clicking the Calculate button to see the takings so far today! Business is looking good. And so is your shop. Your customers are impressed, and you have the right tool to give yourself the full control you need, and have been waiting for, to progress your business still further.
\par Spend your time getting to know ProffittCenter Pro and all of its many features. You will be rewarded handsomely, in increased profits and reduced losses.
\par ProffittCenter Pro - more than just a pretty face.
\par 
\par \plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 3.\tab Hardware
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_hardware}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_hardware}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 3.1.\tab Hardware
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {CCD}}}{\v{\xe {receipt}}}{\v{\xe {receipt printer}}}{\v{\xe {cash drawer}}}{\v{\xe {Internet}}}{\v{\xe {ProffittCenter}}}{\v{\xe {printer}}}{\v{\xe {computer}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The minimum hardware requirements are a standard PC with a processor speed of 300MHz or greater, with keyboard, monitor, simple sound system and mouse; and a standard ink jet printer, for reports. 
\par To this, you should add a laser hands free scanner, to read in the bar codes. Choose one with a USB interface. CCD scanners are a cheaper option, but can be tedious to use in practice, as they need to be held at the correct distance from the bar code, and generally require a trigger button to be pressed which precludes hands-free operation. They are unsuitable for reading the larger case codes used in the delivery screen.
\par Most practical situations would require the addition of a receipt printer and cash drawer. We recommend a serial thermal receipt printer, which is fast, quiet and can include an automatic paper cut-off mechanism. Cash drawers attach to an outlet at the back of the receipt printer. An ink jet printer will still be required for reports. A receipt printer is required to print off lists for stock counting.
\par A customer pole display is a useful addition. One with 'pass-thru' for a serial receipt printer is required.
\par There is no need to locate and install Windows drivers for your receipt printer or scanner, as they are not used by the program. Supported printers are selected in the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul settings\plain\f4\fs24  screen, reached from the file menu. Set the printer and pole display to ESC/POS emulation. The drive program is included within the program.
\par If buying a computer, choose a processor speed of at least 1GHz and with the current low memory prices, at very least 2GB of RAM. A hard disk needs to be at least 20GB and preferably 100GB. A 19-inch LCD monitor is recommended. A CD R/W drive is definitely desirable for backups or a memory stick can be used.
\par An Internet connection is needed for updates to the program and for e-mail support or for accessing an online database. Future extensions with exciting possibilities may require access to the Internet. 
\par We can supply extension kits to convert your existing computer or complete turnkey systems, pre-loaded with ProffittCenter for maximum convenience. See the web site at \plain\f4\fs24\cf1\ul www.proffittcenter.org\plain\f4\fs24  for the latest prices.
\par The program is developed to run on Windows XP but should run on other operating systems. The installer is windows specific. Try WebStart or download the jar file for other operating systems.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Seconduserequipment}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Seconduserequipment}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 3.2.\tab Second-hand equipment
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {second-hand}}}{\v{\xe {receipt printers}}}{\v{\xe {dot matrix}}}{\v{\xe {thermal}}}{\v{\xe {code 39}}}{\v{\xe {3 of 9}}}{\v{\xe {EAN}}}{\v{\xe {UPC}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Having acquired free software, some retailers have built successful systems using only second-hand equipment for the ultimate in a low cost approach. There is little to fault with this approach. Much of the equipment available has years of useful life left, and there is a steady supply of equipment, due to shop closures and liquidations. (EPOS didn't stop them failing!)
\par Receipt printers are available with either dot matrix or thermal mechanisms. Dot matrix types are noisier and will occasionally need a new ribbon, whereas thermal printers need special, but readily available paper; but both are usable. Interfaces are currently serial, or parallel, but USB is available on newer units. The program can accept either serial or parallel. USB may present a problem. The program can accept Epson ESC/POS standard. Other widths can be catered for by adjusting the characters to a line setting in the settings screen. Printers are often set up by internal dip switches. To test current settings, press and hold the Form Feed switch while switching on the printer and it should print out a test strip together with information that will show the settings. A printer manual can often be downloaded from the Internet, but in the absence of this, you could try adjusting switch setting by trial and error. A serial printer should be set to 8 bits, no parity, dtr/dsr, 9600 baud and one stop bit. Note that you will require a serial printer cable and not a null modem cable.
\par Scanners can be keyboard wedge, (a Y-shaped lead that sits between computer and keyboard,) serial, or USB interface. See the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul section\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  on setting up a serial scanner. If the scanner works for your products, fine. If not, you may need to re-program it. First locate the manual on the Internet, and print it. If your scanner is too old to be supported, download a later scanner by the same manufacturer and try using that one. Scanners are programmed by scanning special bar codes printed in their manual. You need to program it to read type 39 codes (or 3of 9) and the various EAN and UPC codes on offer. Default settings are commonly acceptable, but changing such things as inter-character delay can be helpful.
\par Cash drawers are generally compatible, and plug into the back of the receipt printer. Make sure that you have the correct lead, as they are not too readily available. 
\par New equipment is also to be recommended. New receipt printers will have a drop in facility for paper; this is very useful if you have a customer waiting for a receipt. ProffittCenter can supply recommended compatible equipment so visit the web site at www.proffittcenter.org for current hardware prices. \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Serialscanners}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Serialscanners}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 3.3.\tab Serial scanners
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {serial scanner}}}{\v{\xe {keyboard wedge}}}{\v{\xe {XP}}}{\v{\xe {How do I use a serial scanner}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\li720\fi-360\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 Many people have access to a serial scanner instead of a keyboard wedge or USB type. This procedure will enable such a scanner to be used. The procedure shown below is for Windows XP.\plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par \plain\f11\fs24 1.\tab Go to Start -> Settings -> Control Panel -> Accessibility
\par 
\par 2.\tab Select the General tab, tick Support Serial Devices
\par 
\par 3.\tab Click Settings, select Com Port (normally Com1, but try others if necessary)
\par 4.\tab Select 9600 baud
\par 
\par 5.\tab Accept these changes
\par 6.\tab With XP only, in Classic view, Go to Start -> Settings -> Control Panel ->User Accounts and then
\par 7.\tab Disable Fast User Switching
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f11\fs24 8.\tab In XP we have found it necessary to have log-in enabled, even if there is only one user.
\par 
\par Windows vista and windows 7 do not have this feature any more so use the free utility ACC KEYS which can be downloaded from http://www.aacinstitute.org/Resources/ProductsandServices/aackeys.html
\par 1)Download a file and save it somewhere where it will not be deleted as it doesn't have an installer.
\par 2)Double click on file, set com port to which scanner is connected and set baud rate to whatever your barcode is set to (usually 9600 is ok)
\par 3) Tick an option to run on startup
\par 4) if all is well scanner should work now, if not make sure that you selected correct port and baud rate for your scanner\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Laptop}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Laptop}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 3.4.\tab Laptops
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {laptop}}}{\v{\xe {USB}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 A laptop may also be used to run the system. This has the immediate advantage of being able to continue working after a power failure. It also leads to a compact counter-top solution.
\par We would recommend a USB scanner and serial printer. A single line scanner should be able to run off the laptop's power supply. The receipt printer will require mains input, but it will be possible to continue working without receipts. The parallel or USB port can be used for connection to a report printer. A second display may be connected for customer use, mirroring the laptop's screen. This can also be achieved with a television screen with the appropriate connecting leads.
\par Some changes have been made to accommodate the limited keyboard of a laptop. In particular, the .n instead of *n for a multiplier avoids the use of the shift key. Some users have added a USB numeric keypad for convenience.
\par If your laptop lacks a serial port, you can experiment with a USB to serial converter.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_LAYOUT}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_LAYOUT}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 3.5.\tab Layout
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {keyboard}}}{\v{\xe {cash drawer}}}{\v{\xe {sales screen}}}{\v{\xe {parallel}}}{\v{\xe {printer}}}{\v{\xe {How do I build a system?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 You can arrange the monitor on the counter, at right angles, so that both the sales assistant and the customer can view the sales screen at the same time. This should be to the right of the salesperson, with the standard keyboard positioned on the left. This will ensure that the numeric keypad, with all the most commonly used keys, is easy to reach. The cash drawer can be used as a base on which the monitor and receipt printer can be placed. The laser scanner stand should be attached to the counter adjacent to the cash drawer. The computer, in a tower case, can be placed within the counter, below the cash drawer. The cash drawer is similar in size to a standard cash register.
\par It will be necessary to drill some holes for the cables. Typical cable lengths are video: 1.5m, serial receipt printer: 2m, parallel printer cable: up to 3m, scanner: 1m. The connection from the receipt printer to the cash drawer is short \endash  0.5m. The telephone connection can be easily extended to reach the computer with standard telephone extension cables. 
\par A pole display is advised. We prefer the pass-trough variety. ESC?POS is the standard interface.
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 4.\tab Database
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_database}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_database}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 4.1.\tab Databases
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {TEMPA}}}{\v{\xe {product}}}{\v{\xe {temporary}}}{\v{\xe {empty database}}}{\v{\xe {VAT}}}{\v{\xe {department}}}{\v{\xe {TEMPB}}}{\v{\xe {video}}}{\v{\xe {agency}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 When starting with an empty database, it is necessary to create some entries before the system is of any use. Products are created on the fly by the sales screen, but if not defined at the time, they are created with a temporary SKU assignment, Default.
\par To make record creation simpler, some entries are left in the empty database, such as VAT rates, and Departments. These can be modified, deleted and added to as required, but it is important that this is done before adding stock and product records. Once a record is referred to by one of these, it can no longer be deleted. The Stock database is left with two entries called Default and TempB for temporary assignments to zero rated and standard rated stock. The first entry is required by the system and should not be deleted. The Department database is set up with departments. These can be deleted or modified, but three must remain. These are Default', Video and Agency. Agency covers money taken for a third party such as PayPoint. The program uses these three.
\par Similarly, once a sales record refers to a product, the product can no longer be deleted.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_REPAIR}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_REPAIR}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 4.2.\tab Repairing a damaged database
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {damage}}}{\v{\xe {index}}}{\v{\xe {ProffittCenter}}}{\v{\xe {repair}}}{\v{\xe {alias}}}{\v{\xe {restore}}}{\v{\xe {How do I repair a damaged database?}}}{\v{\xe {cashing up}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 There are occasions when databases get damaged. This usually means that the various indexes are no longer in step with the data in the table. In most cases, the damage can be recoverable. There are many free tools available to perform this work with a MySQL database. You should investigate these before committing many hours to creating data.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_IMPORT}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_IMPORT}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 4.3.\tab Importing a database
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {csv}}}{\v{\xe {comma separated values}}}{\v{\xe {format}}}{\v{\xe {spreadsheet}}}{\v{\xe {barcode}}}{\v{\xe {product}}}{\v{\xe {price}}}{\v{\xe {new product}}}{\v{\xe {How do I bring in data from another system?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Accessed from the File menu, this allows data to be imported from ProffittCenter Solo. The data will be as coma separated values - a CSV file. 
\par The Solo version has an option to export the database as a csv file using File|Database|Export to Pro. To import a file in the Pro version, select File|Import and then locate the file, normally in the My Documents folder.
\par After selecting the file to be imported using the conventional File Open Dialog, the file is automatically read in. The process can take some time to complete. Sales data is not imported.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_backingup}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_backingup}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 4.4.\tab Backing up
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Facilities are built into ProffittCenter to back up the MySQL database to an online server over the Internet every time you shut down ProffittCenter on the computer with the server running on it. In the Settings screen are two entries: Backup email address and Backup password. The backup email address and password are just the values for a gmail account which may be your own or one you have created just to hold your backups. The files will have the name 'tillDumpxx.sql where xx is the numeric day of the month. Do not switch off your computer until the backing up is complete. This may take some time. Subsequently, a log file of any errors is saved locally in My Documents/ProffittCenter Reports. This is not dated, so only one file will be available when you look.
\par If you need to restore the database at any time, download the latest backup file from your gmail account, and then run the sql file using phpmyadmin, or other database management tool. (I always use the free version of Navicat)
\par An alternative and somewhat easier backing up solution is now provided. Just install the free  software, and everything will be taken care of.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 5.\tab Sales screen
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_salesscreen}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_salesscreen}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.1.\tab Sales
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {scanner}}}{\v{\xe {laser scanner}}}{\v{\xe {barcode}}}{\v{\xe {multiple}}}{\v{\xe {delete}}}{\v{\xe {lay away}}}{\v{\xe {training}}}{\v{\xe {price encoded}}}{\v{\xe {10000 code}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24\b For normal sales operations:
\par \plain\f4\fs24 Type or scan the product code followed by the Tab or Enter key (a laser scanner can automatically append a tab to scanned bar codes when correctly set up). [Unknown products will need to be scanned twice to avoid accepting fragments of bar codes as product IDs. After the second entry, the label next to the entry box will change to 'Enter description...' ]
\par 
\par \pard\qc\plain\f4\fs24\b Or
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs24 Type a \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul hotkey \plain\f4\fs24 followed by the Tab or Enter key, or for multiple products, type the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul hotkey\plain\f4\fs24  followed by the number to be sold and then the Tab or Enter key
\par \pard\qc\plain\f4\fs24\b 
\par Or
\par 
\par \pard\tx284\plain\f4\fs24 Type any three or more letters \endash  a list of product descriptions will appear in the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Alpha Lookup\plain\f4\fs24  screen, containing words starting with these letters, one of which can be selected with a left click of the mouse or the up and down arrow keys followed by the Enter key. The word entered does not have to be the first word of the description
\par \pard\qc\tx284\plain\f4\fs24\b 
\par Or
\par 
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs24 Type '10000'  followed by a four digit 10000 code to sell items identified by a four digit code applied with a pricing gun.
\par  
\par The last product sold can be deleted by pressing the delete key.
\par To delete the sale of a product that is not the last item on the sales screen, select the item by the use of the up and down arrow keys, or using a mouse, and then press the delete key. After an item has been selected, the quantity may be modified by entering\plain\f4\fs24\b  '\plain\f4\fs24 *n' or '.n' followed by the Enter key or by pressing the Enter key alone to increase the quantity by 1. After these operations, the line selected will return to the last line of the sale.
\par To delete all of the items in a sale with one operation, simply hold the shift key down when pressing the delete key.
\par 
\par \plain\f4\fs24\b Price encoding\plain\f4\fs24 
\par Price encoded products are handled correctly, both for existing products and for new products that are entered.
\par 
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Multiplesales}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Multiplesales}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.2.\tab Multiple sales
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24\b To sell multiple identical products\plain\f4\fs24 :
\par Sell a single product as normal and then type \plain\f4\fs24\b *n\plain\f4\fs24  or \plain\f4\fs24\b .n \plain\f4\fs24 and then the Enter key, where n is the number to be sold. The value of n can be negative for refunds (return to stock). 
\par \pard\qc\plain\f4\fs24\b Or
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs24 Type \plain\f4\fs24\b n\plain\f4\fs24  and then scan a single product where n is the number to be sold and n is in the range 2 to 9. 
\par \pard\qc\plain\f4\fs24\b Or
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs24 Press Enter on its own after a product sale to increase the number of products sold by one.
\par 
\par The number of any products sold, when incorrect, can be corrected by selecting the line first if it is not the last line and then typing \plain\f4\fs24\b *n\plain\f4\fs24  or \plain\f4\fs24\b .n\plain\f4\fs24  followed by the Enter key, where n is the correct number to be sold.
\par \plain\f4\fs24\b Negative sales\plain\f4\fs24 
\par To sell a negative quantity (i.e. to accept back stock that has been previously sold) just type a minus followed by Enter after the initial sale. Note that pressing the Enter key subsequently will increase the number by -1 - that is if we have a sale of -1 items and then press the Enter key again, there will be -2 items sold. Another way of accomplishing the same effect is to type \plain\f4\fs24\b -\plain\f4\fs24  (minus) before scanning the product bar code. If a product returned, is not fit for resale, proceed in the same way, but subsequently '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul waste\plain\f4\fs24 ' or '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul return\plain\f4\fs24 ' the product as a separate sale.
\par \plain\f4\fs24\b Finally\plain\f4\fs24 
\par The operation of the sales screen initially seem complicated by the large number of ways of achieving the same result; each operator is free to choose whichever method seems easiest at the time. There is provision for a training mode by creating an operator with an authority of '5'. With this operator using the machine, no sales are recorded so that the operator is free to practice using the different methods of operation.
\par 
\par 
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_hotkey}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_hotkey}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.3.\tab Hot Key
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {hot key}}}{\v{\xe {PayPoint}}}{\v{\xe {VAT}}}{\v{\xe {barcodes}}}{\v{\xe {greengrocery}}}{\v{\xe {penny sweets}}}{\v{\xe {weight}}}{\v{\xe {count}}}{\v{\xe {product}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Any single letter key in the range 'a' to 'z', (or, alternatively, letters in the range 'A' to 'Z',) are used to ease entry for common products. Products sold by weight or count, such as greengrocery or penny sweets, can be assigned to a hot key with a price of one penny. The letter 'a' key is allocated for zero rate VAT sales and the letter 'b' key to standard rate VAT sales. The letter 'u' key is allocated to Agency sales such as PayPoint and the letter 'l' key to late videos.
\par The letter a or A is converted into a code of 1000001 and the letter z or 'Z' to 1000026, with appropriate values for intermediate letters. Hot keys are created, just as other products, by using these numbers instead of Bar codes.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_10000code}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_10000code}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.4.\tab 10000 Codes
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {10000 code}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 With products without Bar codes, it is convenient to use a pricing gun to label them with a four-digit code. As the code alone would be interpreted as a cash tender, 10000 is put before to the code for data entry. Reference to "10000 codes" is a convenient mnemonic to remind staff of the need to enter 10000 first. 
\par If a new product is to be created with a '10000' code, enter the full code as a product ID, which includes the initial 10000.
\par The new product screen has a button that will assign an unused '10000' code.
\par In the sales screen, press the # key to fill in the 1000 preamble for the 10000 code.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_priceover}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_priceover}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.5.\tab Price Over
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {manager}}}{\v{\xe {owner}}}{\v{\xe {authority}}}{\v{\xe {@}}}{\v{\xe {price over}}}{\v{\xe {offers}}}{\v{\xe {discount}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 This feature allows an operator to vary the price at the point of sale. The item is sold in the normal way. Then enter the at symbol, @, (or alternativle, the character =, which avoids the use of the shift key,) followed by the price in pence. The selling price is adjusted for the current or selected line only. The price of the product in the product table is \plain\f3\fs24\cf0\b not \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 changed. Any items sold subsequently will be at the original price, even during the current sale. \plain\f4\fs24\cf0 If an offer is in use on the product, then it will not apply to a priced over item. \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 If only one item of several is to be reduced, then it needs to be on a separate line, so deal with it first..
\par There is interaction between price over and \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul discount\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 . See this section for details.
\par \plain\f4\fs24 This operation is restricted to those with the manager or owner authority. If the operator does not have authority, a dialog box is displayed and an owner/manager can scan their pass to allow the price over.
\par The maximum price that can be entered as a price over is \'a31200. The price may be increased as well as reduced. The need for this might arise if you were to use the program to keep track of auction sales in addition to shop sales.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Discounts}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Discounts}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.6.\tab Discounts
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {discount}}}{\v{\xe {%}}}{\v{\xe {offer}}}{\v{\xe {manager}}}{\v{\xe {owner}}}{\v{\xe {authority}}}{\v{\xe {priced over}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 A discount can be offered on the last item scanned, or any selected item, by typing the percentage discount followed by the % symbol \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 (or alternativle, the character /, which avoids the use of shift key,) \plain\f4\fs24 followed by the Enter key. For example; a ten percent discount is achieved by just entering 10%! \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 If offers are in affect on the discounted product, then any change due to the offer will not be applied to a discounted item.  If only one item of several is to be discounted, then it needs to be on a separate line.
\par If a whole bill is to be discounted, prior to accepting a tender, hold down the shift key when pressing enter. So for 10% discount type 10% and press shift/Enter and ten per cent discount will be applied to each line of the bill.
\par If a discounted item is subsequently \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul priced over\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 , the discount will be maintained on the item. So an item at \'a310 with at10% discount will sell at \'a39. If this item is subsequently priced over at \'a35, the 10% discount will be applied to this price, making it sell at \'a34.50. \plain\f4\fs24 These operations are restricted to those with the manager or owner authority. If the operator does not have authority, a dialog box is displayed and an owner/manager can scan their pass to allow the discount.
\par 
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_alphalookup}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_alphalookup}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.7.\tab Alpha Lookup
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {alpha lookup}}}{\v{\xe {stock take}}}{\v{\xe {product modify}}}{\v{\xe {shelf label}}}{\v{\xe {How do I find a product by name?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 In all locations where a product bar code is expected, entering three or more characters will bring up the Alpha Lookup screen. For this to work, all characters have to be alphabetic characters. The Alpha Lookup screen will show a list of matching product descriptions. Entering more characters can further restrict the search. It is not necessary to type in the starting characters of the first word, as the match is performed of each word in the product description. So typing bleach may result in a list including 'HS Bleach 1l', 'HS Thick Bleach 1l', Domestos Bleach 1.5l' and Bleach, Value 1l.
\par Products can be selected with the mouse or by using the up/down arrow keys. The typed description will then be replaced by the product bar code. The last column contains a single digit, 0 to 9. If this digit is pressed, that line will be selected. If there are more than ten lines, the remainder are not numbered.
\par Each line of the display contains a retail price. This allows for the correct selection of products with identical descriptions but different prices. The next one to the end of the line, after the product description, shows the number in stock. It is often the most convenient way of checking the current stockholding, from the sales screen; useful for answering customer requests. Pressing Escape will abort the lookup, afterwards. The product code (barcode) is also shown to distinguish similar products.
\par Products that have their 'StockType' set to Stop are not included in the selection shown. This is a useful feature to remove products that are no longer sold from the alpha display.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Pennyitems}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Pennyitems}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.8.\tab Penny items
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {greengrocery}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Multiple items priced at 1 penny (UK) are treated slightly differently to others. Say we have the key g set as a hotkey for all greengrocery sold, each sold at 1p, and we enter g35 to indicate that greengrocery worth 35p has been sold. This is then displayed as 1 item at 35p rather than 35 items at 1p. If we subsequently try to modify the number sold, say be pressing the enter key to increase by one, the number sold will increase to two at 35p. This representation is not restricted to hotkeys; any product priced at 1p will be treated the same way. This change was made as customers were sometimes confused by the unmodified display. The use of the penny and the pound in these discussions, does not mean that the facilities are limited to just this currency. ProffittCenter is an international program.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Zeropriceitems}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Zeropriceitems}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.9.\tab Zero price items
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {zero}}}{\v{\xe {price encoded}}}{\v{\xe {fish}}}{\v{\xe {price entry}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Items that have a zero price recorded cause a Price Entry dialog to be displayed, when sold. This does not change the price of the product permanently; just for this sale. Such items can be used for goods which are counted for stock control, but which do not have a fixed price. Loose cut cheese would be an example. Price encoded bar codes are a better solution, where this is possible. Another example would be live (aquarium) fish which are charged for depending on their size. Bar codes are not practical, here.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_trackeditems}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_trackeditems}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.10.\tab Tracking
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {Tracked department}}}{\v{\xe {'Customers'}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 There is a need to track the sale of certain items. A common example is a mobile phone, which can be returned months after an initial sale. It is necessary to be able to identify when a particular phone was sold and to whom. Each phone has an individual barcode (or id code to be typed) and this must be somehow be attached to the sale.
\par To track an item, the item must first belong to a '\plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Tracked department\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 '. On scanning the item, the first step is display the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul 'Customers'\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  table to select a customer or add a new one. Then the items individual id is scanned (or typed) and this is saved when the sale is completed.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_priceencoding}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_priceencoding}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.11.\tab Price encoding
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 There is not a universal standard for price encoded barcodes but it is hoped that what has been implemented will be suitable for most applications. When creating a new product with the 'New Product' screen, if the barcode \plain\f3\fs24\cf0\i might \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 be a price encoded barcode, there is an drop down box labeled 'Encoded' that can select one of three options:
\par \pard\li200\fi-200\tx200{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent200{\pntxtb\'b7}}\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Normal\plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Price encoded\plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Weight encoded.\plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par \pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Choose the correct setting and in the case of 'Weight encoded' , enter the price per kg in the price box. For 'Price encoded', the price will be set to 0.
\par When the product is subsequently scanned, the correct price will be shown.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_multipacks}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_multipacks}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.12.\tab Multipacks
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 There is sometimes a need to have multi packs and single packs linked to a single SKU. If this is not done, then it is necessary to book out the multipack and treat the individual items as a fresh delivery each time a multipack is split.
\par Let us for example consider Stella cans sold singly at \'a31 each. You could also sell whole cases (24 cans) at \'a322 a case. The case would be recognised by the case barcode. We are not discussing offers here. The singles and cases are treated as different products being sold at different prices. What we require is for the stock level of Stella cans to be reduced by 24 every time a case is sold.
\par This is achieved by changing the multipack quantity from its' default value of 1 to 24 in the New Product dialog. As this makes no sense, unless the product is linked to an existing product, a link must also be made in the Sku drop down box before this can be effected.
\par Note that when stocktaking, it is now the number of cans of Stella that will be counted, even if cases are listed.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Tracking}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Tracking}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.13.\tab Tracking
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {!}}}{\v{\xe {alpha lookup}}}{\v{\xe {tracking}}}{\v{\xe {mobile phones}}}{\v{\xe {tracked department'}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 In some situations, it is necessary to track the customer name for certain purchased items. An example of this would be the sale of mobile phones, each individually identified by a serial number. If one is later brought back for repair, the customer name can be entered, and the details of the sale recovered, allowing the serial number to be checked, and the date of purchase.
\par Products to be tracked are distinguished by being in a '\plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul tracked department'\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 . To ensure that the product can still be identified by the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul alpha lookup\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  process, the ! should be separated from the rest of the description by an additional space.
\par When a tracked product is sold, there is a beep and the customer screen is displayed. If the customer is already on record, the appropriate record is clicked prior to clicking on the OK button, or simply double clicked. If the customer is not on record, clicking the OK button, or pressing the enter key, will bring up the new customer screen, so that details can be entered.
\par Once this is done, a screen is displayed for entry of the item code, and then the OK button clicked to complete the sale. When the sale is completed, information is stored in the sales table for later use.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_restrictedproducts}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_restrictedproducts}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 5.14.\tab Restricted products
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Product can be restricted either by setting an age limit or by a 'phamacist only' requirement. A restriction is set in place by imposing the restriction on the department the product is in. For age restrictions, set the age in the restriction field of the department - i.e. 18 for a minimum age of 18. For pharmacist only put a letter p in the field.
\par When a restricted product is sold, a question is asked via the screen, and the operator responds with a 'y' for yes. Any other key press is treated as a no and the sale is not completed.
\par If an age related product is sold, the system wi;ll not ask again for the same customer.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 6.\tab Tenders
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_cashtender}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_cashtender}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.1.\tab Cash tender
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {cash}}}{\v{\xe {tender}}}{\v{\xe {returned}}}{\v{\xe {1000 codes}}}{\v{\xe {refund}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24\b Making a cash tender\plain\f4\fs24 
\par To enter cash tendered, type in the amount in pence followed by the Enter key. All values up to 1000000 (\'a310,000) are treated as cash. 
\par If it is found necessary to exceed this limit, press the shift key at the same time as pressing the Enter key.
\par If cash is to be returned to a customer after a \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul refund\plain\f4\fs24 , type 0 (zero) followed by the Enter key.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_DEBIT}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_DEBIT}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.2.\tab Debit
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {debit}}}{\v{\xe {credit}}}{\v{\xe {cash back}}}{\v{\xe {How do I accept payment by Debit card?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Debit and credit cards may be accepted in payment of a sale by pressing the function key 'F5' or by selecting Payment|Debit with the mouse. A minimum amount of \'a35 by default, or to the value set in the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul settings\plain\f4\fs24  screen, is required. If this condition is not met, then a warning message is displayed.
\par \pard\li1440\fi-1440\tx1440\tx2000\plain\f4\fs24 {\field{\*\fldinst{INCLUDEPICTURE "DebitWarning.bmp" MERGEFORMAT}}} 
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs24 The dialog that appears shows the total to be paid. Stepping on to the next entry by pressing Enter moves to the Cash back drop down box. This may be activated by left clicking the mouse or by using the Down Arrow key. Cash back of 5, 10, 15 or 20 is allowed. Remember that cash back is not allowed with credit cards. When your separate PDQ or other terminal accepts the card, press Enter twice more to accept the payment. Pressing Escape aborts the payment method.
\par {\field{\*\fldinst{INCLUDEPICTURE "DebitDialog..bmp" MERGEFORMAT}}}
\par On-line processing is not implemented yet.
\par Debit or credit card payment is not acceptable for PayPoint or other agency payments if these form a part of the sale. This restriction, and the minimum transaction value, can be overridden by pressing the shift key while selecting the debit payment option on the menu bar with the mouse, if the operator has owner or manager authority.
\par There is no minimum set for refunds on debit or credit cards.
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_COUPONS}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_COUPONS}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.3.\tab Coupons
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {coupon}}}{\v{\xe {milk token}}}{\v{\xe {expiry}}}{\v{\xe {How do I accept money off coupons?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Coupons may be scanned at the point of sale or can be entered manually by pressing the 'F7' key. Scanning will enter the correct monetary value but the expiry date still needs to be checked manually. Coupons with an undefined value, such as milk tokens, will bring up a screen for the true value to be entered.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Splittenders}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Splittenders}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.4.\tab Split tenders
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 It is possible to do split tenders, such as part payment by debit card, and part by cash. In all cases, the cash tender should be the last entry.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_refunds}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_refunds}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.5.\tab Refunds
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {wastes}}}{\v{\xe {returns}}}{\v{\xe {refunds}}}{\v{\xe {exchange}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 If a customer brings back an item for a refund and it is decided to repay the customer, then type a minus sign '-' and then scan the item. Alternatively, the item can be scanned first and then the minus sign pressed followed by the Enter or Tab key. Every item in a sale can be returned at one go by typing - (minus) followed by the Enter key whilst holding the Shift key down. The amount to be paid will be shown as negative, indicating a refund. Entering a zero followed by the enter key will then open the cash drawer. All operators can perform this action. Refunds can be performed as part of a sale, if desired, such as when items are exchanged. After these operations are complete, the item will have been returned to stock. If the item is not fit for resale, it is set aside, and at a later stage, it is \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul wasted\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 , or \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul returnable waste\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 , as appropriate. 
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_wastes}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_wastes}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.6.\tab Wastes
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {wastes}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Wastes are products that are not fit for sale. When a product is wasted, the stock levels are adjusted.
\par To '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Waste\plain\f4\fs24 ' stock, when products are not fit for sale, first sell the items \endash  multiple products or different products can be wasted at one time \endash  and then scan the waste bar code or type \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 1000031\plain\f4\fs24  and the Enter key to complete the sale. \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 A keyboard shortcut of ? enters the number 100003; add a 1, followed by Tab to create the code for waste. 
\par \plain\f4\fs24 
\par See also \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul returns\plain\f4\fs24 .
\par \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 The bar code for wastes can be printed out using the \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul print bar codes\plain\f8\fs24\cf0  option.
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_returnablewastes}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_returnablewastes}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.7.\tab Returnable wastes
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {returns}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Returnable wastes are products that are not fit for sale but for which a full credit may be claimed from the manufacturer. When products are returned, the stock levels are adjusted.
\par To '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Return\plain\f4\fs24 ' stock, when products are not fit for sale but will subsequently be credited by a supplier, sell as normal - multiple products or different products can be wasted at one time - and then complete the sale by scanning the returnable wastes bar code or type \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 1000032\plain\f4\fs24  and the Enter key. \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 A keyboard shortcut of ? enters the number 100003; typing a 2 followed by Tab completes the code for return.\plain\f4\fs24 
\par \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 The bar code for returns can be printed out using the \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul print bar codes\plain\f8\fs24\cf0  option.
\par Refunds can be in cash or debit/credit card.
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Ownuse}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Ownuse}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.8.\tab Own use
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {takings}}}{\v{\xe {own use}}}{\v{\xe {operator}}}{\v{\xe {owner}}}{\v{\xe {net}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 For products taken for the retailer's own use, sell as normal, and then scan the own use bar code or type \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 1000036\plain\f4\fs24  followed by the Enter key. Own use purchases are charged for at cost in the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul takings\plain\f4\fs24 , and no payment is expected to be made. The operator must be the owner.
\par Own use purchases are assigned to a particular customer, who, to distinguish him from other customers, has an Account name (not customer name) of  'Own use'.
\par \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 The bar code own use can be printed out using the \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul print bar codes\plain\f8\fs24\cf0  option. A keyboard shortcut of ? enters the number 100003; typing a 6 followed by Tab completes the code for own use.
\par Note that the net figure in the \plain\f8\fs24\cf2\ul takings\plain\f8\fs24\cf0  report now includes own use purchases at cost, whereas in earlier versions, this figure excluded own use.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Receipts}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Receipts}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 6.9.\tab Receipts
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {receipt}}}{\v{\xe {F10}}}{\v{\xe {message}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Receipts are only printed after the sale is complete. When a receipt is required, press the 'Print Screen' key - the one labeled 'Print/SysRq' on most keyboards, at any time after the first item is sold, up until the sales screen is cleared. A receipt is printed out on the receipt printer selected in the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul settings\plain\f4\fs24  screen. . A receipt for a past sale can be printed by locating the sale in the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Tables|Sales\plain\f4\fs24 ' screen and pressing the 'Print Screen' key or clicking the Printer button.\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par The normal mode of operation is with a receipt only being printed on demand. If, however, a receipt is required after every sale, there is a checkbox option for this choice in the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul settings\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen.
\par There is also an option to print receipts whenever the sales total exceeds a fixed amount. Enter the amount in pounds in the box adjacent to the 'Receipts always' checkbox. \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 7.\tab Other till functions
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_paidout}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_paidout}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 7.1.\tab Paid outs
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {paid out}}}{\v{\xe {supplier}}}{\v{\xe {cheque}}}{\v{\xe {print cheque}}}{\v{\xe {authority}}}{\v{\xe {reason}}}{\v{\xe {parking}}}{\v{\xe {Windows}}}{\v{\xe {How do I pay for goods from the cash drawer?}}}{\v{\xe {cash limit}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 To pay money out to a supplier, press the Function key 'F9'. The screen shown below appears, if the operator has manager or owner authority.
\par The default entry is the Reason drop down box. Type in the reason for the payout. When the Paid out key is next activated, the reason will appear in the drop down box. Next, the amount, in pence, is typed in. Then press the Enter key to accept the entries. The cash drawer will then open.
\par Money paid into the cash drawer, say a refund from a supplier can be handled by a paid in. Simply hold the shift key down when pressing F9.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
