\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 8.\tab Embedded barcodes
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_embeddedbarcodes}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_embeddedbarcodes}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 8.1.\tab Embedded barcodes
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Some barcodes have the price or the weight encoded in the barcode; for a detailed description of this, see WikiAnswers. 
\par The most common formats are:
\par UPC-A: 2IIIIIVPPPPC
\par UPC-B & EAN-13: 02IIIIIVPPPPC
\par In these formats the "02" or "2" are the left-most digits of barcode. 
\par The 'I' characters are the item code, and the 'P' characters are the price or weight codes. The 'V' and 'C' are check digits.
\par It is not possible to enter such codes at the sales screen like other products, but if such a code is scanned into the 'New product' screen either from delivery or starting stock screens, then there is automatically an additional option available - to choose encoded by weight or by price. When one of these is chosen, the barcode is stripped down to the initial digits and then the rest replaced with zeroes. With price encoded products, the price entry is not relevant and a zero will be stored. For weight encoded products, the weight is specified in grams and the price entered should be the price per kilogram.
\par The encoded products can be examined in the 'Table|Encoded products' screen.
\par When sold via the sales screen, the normal actions of the Enter key to increase quantity by one, and to multiply by n by typing *n, do not work. Such products should always be scanned singly.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 9.\tab Bill payments
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_billpayments}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_billpayments}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 9.1.\tab Bill payments
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {Agency}}}{\v{\xe {Bill payments}}}{\v{\xe {Excluded}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 In the UK there is a service called PayPoint that many shops participate in, that allows money to be collected for various bill payment facilities. There are also competitors who offer a similar service, and no doubt the same sercice is offered in other countries. The money collected is not a part of the shop's turnover; the shop is collecting it on behalf of service as an agent and for this reason, the payments are refered to in ProffittCenter as Agency payments. They are identified by being given a tax code of 6 - Excluded. The term Excluded can be re-named, but the ID must remain unchanged. Any product with an Excluded tax rate will not be included in the shop's takings and a separate tally will be maintained in the Takings screen.
\par Commonly, a hotkey will be used, as the payments may be variable. We used the letter U for utility, so that to pay \'a310, one entered u1000.
\par When the money has been collected, the payment details are entered into the terminal provided by the service and the transaction completed. It is normally complicated to reverse a payment with the system, so it is important to collect the money before entering the details. For this reason, the amounts involved are shown after the sale is complete in the same space as the date is normally shown. 
\par Bill payments cannot be paid by cheque or debit card unless authorised by an owner or manager. For individual bill payments, the *n and blank entry (increase by one) will not work.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 10.\tab Offers
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_offer}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_offer}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 10.1.\tab Offers
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {pack offers}}}{\v{\xe {quantity discounts}}}{\v{\xe {offers}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Offers are desirable as a part of the overall offering of any shop. ProffittCenter has a range of offers that can be programmed by an owner or manager. Offers available are currently divided into three groups. These are \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul pack offers\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 , \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul quantity discounts\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  and \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul bin offers\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 . Further offer types may be added in future versions, creating the prospect of an extremely versatile system. The names of the types of offer are not very indicative, and a careful study of the implementation is necessary, if the offers facility is to be fully utilised.
\par There is an interaction between offers, and items sold using the @ function (price over) or a discount given using the % function. In general, if the reduced price is less than the normal price or the offer price, it will be maintained. If this is not true, the two different price reductions are not combined.
\par Where \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul customer discounts\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  are in force, these are combined.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_packoffers}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_packoffers}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 10.2.\tab Pack offers
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {pack offers}}}{\v{\xe {offers}}}{\v{\xe {BOGOF}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Pack offers are offers that apply to one or more products, where a discount is offered whenever a specified number of items are sold. This is best clarified by a few examples. Suppose we wish to sell four packs of Stella at a discount of 20p from the cost of four individual cans. This equates to 5p a can. However, if five cans are purchased, there is no discount given on the fifth can. If a discount were to be required on the fifth can, then a quantity discount is the required offer type. Another example would be the offer of buying any four bars from a range of six chocolate bars for a pound. This can be applied by giving an offer price of 25p to each of the six products. A range of products can be selected for the offer. Consider a cat food - there might be a range of six flavours all covered by the same offer.
\par To set up a pack offer, choose the menu selection Offers|Create and then choose Pack offer in the drop down box.
\par The required first product is scanned, or the alpha lookup function used. Pressing tab moves the focus to the quantity for the offer and then the limit. Leave the limit as zero if there is no limit. Limit values do not stop the sale of more items - they limit the number of items that can be bought at a discount. Additional items are sold at the full price. The normal price will be filled in when enter is pressed.. The offer price will be the price for the pack. In the example of the bars of chocolate above, this would be \'a31. Next, the start and end dates are selected by means of a drop down calendars. Offers only have effect between these dates. If more than one product is required for the offer, click the Add button (or type + in the product box) and then enter the additional product. It is not then be necessary to set a price for the offer. The offer will be automatically inactivated on the day after the end date. \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_quantitydiscounts}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_quantitydiscounts}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 10.3.\tab Quantity discounts
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {quantity discounts}}}{\v{\xe {offers}}}{\v{\xe {discount}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 Quantity discounts\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  are offers that apply to one or more products, where a discount is offered whenever a specified number of items are exceeded. The discount is specified as a percentage. This is best clarified by a few examples. Suppose we wish to sell four packs of Stella at a discount price of 80p when the normal price is \'a31. This equates to 20% reduction. If five cans are purchased, there will also be a discount on all five cans, unlike the pack offer. A range of products can be selected for the offer. Consider a dog food - there might be a range of five flavours, all covered by the same offer of 10p off when you buy three or more.
\par To set up a quantity discount, choose the menu selection Offers|Create and then choose Quantity discount in the drop down box.
\par The required first product is scanned, or the alpha lookup function used. Pressing enter moves the focus to the quantity for the offer and then the limit. Leave the limit as zero if there is no limit. Limit values do not stop the sale of more items - they limit the items that can be bought at a discount. The discount can then be filled in. Next, the start and end dates are selected by means of drop down calendars. If more than one product is required for the offer, click the plus button, and the system will fill in details for subsequent products. The offer will be \plain\f4\fs24\cf0 automatically\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  deactivated on the day after the end date, at program start up. Offers no longer in effect should be deleted using the Offers|View screen, as they can still slow the system down. 
\par For quantity discounts, it is possible to set the pack size to one. This is useful if you would like to put a special price onto an item as an offer, for a limited period.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_binoffer}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_binoffer}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 10.4.\tab Bin offer
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 A bin offer allows for the case when mixed items are sold for a fixed price such as any three of Mars products for 99p even though individual products may have varying prices.
\par To set up a bin offer, choose the menu selection Offers|Create and then choose Bin offer in the drop down box and then press enter. 
\par Select the first product by scanning or by the alpha lookup.
\par Pressing enter moves the focus to the quantity for the offer and then the limit. Leave the limit as zero if there is no limit. Limit values do not stop the sale of more items - they limit the items that can be bought at a discount.
\par Set the quantity to the number needed and the price to the total, and add extra products. In this case, quantity is three and price is 99p.
\par Then press the 'Plus' button to add further products, after entering the product barcode. \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_offers}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_offers}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 10.5.\tab Offers table
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {offers table}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 This table shows the current offers table entries, and is shown when you click on the menu selection Offers|Show. Useful for checking. 
\par X is the threshold for applying an offer, and Y the discounted price. The start and end dates are just that. 
\par If it is necessary to delete an entry, due to an error in entry, or no longer being current, select the row with a mouse, and right-click and select delete offer.
\par The 'Add product' button will allow futher products to be added to an existing offer.
\par There are buttons for deleting an offer or deleting a product from an offer involving multiple products. Additional buttons allow the end date to be changed.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 11.\tab Orders
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_orderingprocess}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_orderingprocess}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 11.1.\tab The ordering process
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {ProffittCenter}}}{\v{\xe {orders}}}{\v{\xe {supplier}}}{\v{\xe {sell by date}}}{\v{\xe {yield}}}{\v{\xe {return on investment}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Ordering with ProffittCenter introduces a number of unique ideas to generate orders with an uncanny intelligence. After using the system for some time, one really begins to believe that the system knows best. Before that time, there is ample opportunity to modify and adapt generated orders, so you never loose control.
\par The first innovation is the estimation of the stock level required. It is best to think of this with the aid of a concrete example. I will base one on my own experience; collecting goods from Booker Cash & Carry, three times a week. On Monday, Wednesday and Friday mornings, and also, occasionally, on Saturday morning. Sunday was our busiest day of the week. Clearly, a fixed level for re-ordering a product might have worked, but it would be sub-optimal. The best answer has to be to look at the past sales record to determine future requirements.
\par The way this is done is explained here. Consider going to Bookers on a Wednesday. The program knows the stock level when generating the order, and the day when fresh stock will be fetched (Friday), after this order is collected. It needs to calculate the number that might be sold between Wednesday morning and Friday morning, and to order a fresh case if this exceeds the number in stock. The best estimate of this number to be sold is obtained by looking at how many were sold in the same time period during the previous week. As this might have been exceptional, the number sold in the same time period two and three weeks before is also calculated, and the worst case (the maximum) selected. This alone would not have any predictive qualities, so in addition to this, three weeks from the previous year are selected, centred on the current time period, but sticking to the same days of the week. As a result of this, items that are seasonal will magically be re-ordered in time.
\par 
\par The second innovation is the integration or stock-checking with the ordering process. It was found in practice that a major reason for errors in orders was errors in stock levels. The worst of these is when a case has not been entered into the system on the previous delivery. In this situation, a second case would be collected, which is not only needlessly expensive, but creates shelf-life problems. To avoid this, each time an order is created, the stock levels of all ordered items should be counted. These levels can be corrected on the order form, and if necessary, the item can be deleted, or a fresh order generated with the corrected values. This has an added benefit in that the levels of stock for items that are ordered are generally low so that counting can be done quickly, and accurately. Once the levels are checked, the stock levels are time stamped, and so will not be included in the next regular stock take, so no additional time is taken.
\par 
\par The third innovation is the calculation of \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul yield\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 , or return on capital invested (roci). No other EPOS system that we know of will provide this vital figure. Yield is the effective return on investment obtained by investing in a particular line of stock. If you are ever in the position of being limited with the amount of cash that you can invest in stock, then common sense dictates that it should be invested in stock with the highest \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul yield\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 . This can be easily done with ProffittCenter. 
\par 
\par The fourth innovation is the calculation of a sell by date. This allows for the rejection of any stock at a cash and carry that will not be sold completely by it's expire date (sell by or use by date in UK).
\par 
\par This has all been explained with just one example. The process is just as applicable to daily milk deliveries, or monthly biscuit orders. Set up the supplier defaults correctly, and all situations are dealt with correctly. Understanding the ordering system is more complicated than with other systems, but is no more complicated to use once defaults have been correctly set up. So persevere and you business will benefit greatly.
\par The MinStockLevel in the stock record is also now included in the calculations. Do not use this as the default for ordering: a value of 1 is sufficient for general use.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_yield}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_yield}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 11.2.\tab Yield
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The yield, or return on capital invested, is the effective interest earned by investing money in stock, given the normal rate of sale. The rate of sale is calculated using the past five weeks, plus a five-week period the year before. Profit is calculated using the last known purchase price and the current selling price. Credit provided is effectively free capital and in cases where the product is likely to sell before being paid for, an arbitrary high value is quoted (10000), as calculation is not possible.
\par Yield can be used to decide whether to buy a product whenever the amount of capital available is limited. The cost of wastes is not used in the calculation.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_ordercreate}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_ordercreate}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 11.3.\tab Generating orders
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {order}}}{\v{\xe {supplier}}}{\v{\xe {default}}}{\v{\xe {greyed}}}{\v{\xe {past sale}}}{\v{\xe {milk}}}{\v{\xe {How do I create an order?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 After using the mouse to select \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul  Orders|Create\plain\f4\fs24 \'85 After selecting a supplier, the Order create form will appear. \plain\lang1024\f4\fs24 
\par \plain\f4\fs24 
\par If the supplier defaults have been set up correctly, the next four entries will be set correctly and the Enter key can be pressed to start the order generation process. If not, then see the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul order parameters\plain\f4\fs24  page. Pressing the OK button will generate an order.
\par Pressing the Cancel button or the Escape key will return immediately to the sales screen without generating an order.
\par The generated order may then be examined by selecting \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Order |View\plain\f4\fs24  on the menu bar.
\par As orders are generated based on past sales, it is not possible to correctly generate an order until there is a past sales history. There should be a minimum of three weeks sales records plus the delivery interval; daily orders such as milk will give correct results after three weeks but orders which are placed monthly will require seven weeks of sales history.
\par The generation of orders can be a lengthy process so do not run it from an active station.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_orderparameters}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_orderparameters}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 11.4.\tab Order parameters
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {delivery date}}}{\v{\xe {delivery time}}}{\v{\xe {credit}}}{\v{\xe {yield}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Days spare: this is the leeway in stock held. If trade never varied, this could be set to zero to guarantee that enough stock was held to meet all requirements. Even if customers were that reliable, it would mean that trade could never increase. Some experiment may be necessary but the default value of one day is a starting point. Keeping to this value for perishable stock will minimise waste; a higher value for stock with a long life and infrequent delivery will reduce out of stocks. It may be beneficial in some circumstances to increase this. We found that with boxed cakes being delivered on a fortnightly cycle, that on the second week the selection was very  poor. While this might be optimal as far as stock is concerned, customers purchasing cake expect a reasonable selection. We found we could increase the days spare stock to seven without seriously affecting waste. 
\par Delivery date: This is the date of the next delivery. Next delivery date: this is the date of the next delivery date after the delivery date. For instance, if going to Cash & Carry on a Wednesday morning, and intending to go again on Friday, enter the date for Friday. This is because we need to calculate how much stock to buy on Wednesday, to last through until Friday.
\par Week's credit: This value is needed to calculate the return on capital investment, labeled \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Yield\plain\f4\fs24 , in the resultant order. \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_orders}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_orders}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 11.5.\tab Orders
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {modify order}}}{\v{\xe {stock level}}}{\v{\xe {shelf}}}{\v{\xe {10000}}}{\v{\xe {alpha lookup}}}{\v{\xe {margins}}}{\v{\xe {memo}}}{\v{\xe {add product}}}{\v{\xe {How do I modify an order?}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The Order screen is used to make changes to orders once they have been generated. It is opened from the menu command \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Orders |View\plain\f4\fs24 . After selecting a supplier, it shows the last order generated for that supplier. The lines in the order are initially in department order, but can be re-sequenced by pressing the yield order or department buttons.
\par Yield order is useful if it is necessary to delete items because of cash constraints. 
\par Department order is useful for stock level checking and forms a useful picking order for cash and carry. 
\par The order can be printed out onto A4 paper using the Print button; if a receipt printer is available, then a condensed form of the order can be printed on the receipt printer by pressing the 'Print' key. If any errors are found in the stock levels, double click on the line in error in the Shelf column. The value will be highlighted (go blue with normal colour schemes) and then the corrected value can be typed in the space, followed by the Enter key.
\par By selecting the No:' column, the number of cases ordered can be modified by over-typing.
\par Clicking on any other column in a row will highlight the whole row. This row can then be deleted by pressing delete on the keyboard. A similar effect is achieved by right clicking the mouse and selecting Delete, by left clicking with the mouse. 
\par The Total cost box shows the cost of the order including any sales tax.
\par The only remaining control is Quit which is self-explanatory. The order is not lost when it is pressed. The Escape key has the same effect. If all of the lines in an order are deleted, the order header is deleted when pressing Quit or moving to a different order. \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 12.\tab Deliveries
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_deliveryentry}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_deliveryentry}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 12.1.\tab Delivery entry
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {delivery}}}{\v{\xe {packs}}}{\v{\xe {price label}}}{\v{\xe {product price}}}{\v{\xe {margin}}}{\v{\xe {new pack}}}{\v{\xe {milk}}}{\v{\xe {How do I enter delivered goods?}}}{\v{\xe {CCD}}}{\v{\xe {scanner}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The Delivery entry screen is accessible either by the menu option \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Stock |Delivery\plain\f4\fs24  or by pressing the function key F11.
\par The 'Select supplier' dialog is shown first. Select the supplier and then press the Enter key to accept.
\par The '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Select delivery\plain\f4\fs24 ' dialog then appears. This show a list of deliveries, identified by their delivery note numbers. Click on one of these and then press Enter or click the OK button. Alternatively, if this is a new delivery, type in the delivery note number (or code) and then click OK; you will then be asked to enter the (delivery note) date.
\par The 'Delivery entry' screen then appears.
\par Then type or scan, the pack code. If the pack is recognised, the remaining boxes are filled in, and entry moves to the Number of packs box with a default value of one. If more than one pack is delivered, type in the number followed by the Enter key. If it is not recognised, the system will issue an error beep. Enter the code a second time to bring up the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul new pack\plain\f4\fs24  screen. Entering the code twice avoids the creation of bogus codes when only a partial scan is completed. The pack codes entered may be the bar code on the pack, the supplier stock code, or an arbitrary code for your convenience. Both letters and numbers are acceptable.
\par For instance, for milk, we use the set of codes pas, 2pas, 4pas for one, two and four pint pasteurised milk. For newspapers, we found it convenient to use the single newspaper bar code as a pack code for a paper. This has the advantage that one is not caught out by new Bar codes at the point of sale. For frozen foods, we use the supplier stock codes shown on the invoice. This allows frozen food to be placed immediately into the freezer, prior to data entry. If an unrecognised code is encountered, it is necessary to retrieve a sample from the freezer to obtain the product bar code. For most other products, we use the pack bar code. It may not be possible to read this with a CCD scanner.
\par For most items obtained singly, other than milk, we have a policy of always buying in two at a time, as this will allow for sales to increase more easily with demand. We then entered a 2 before scanning the single item bar code. This scheme is extendible to higher numbers. The advantage of this, over just using the bar code, is that a common mistake is to scan a bar code after serving a customer without first pressing F11. Without the need for a preceding digit, the item will be recognised as a sale.
\par On pressing the Tab key, the focus moves to the Pack price box. Check this value to see if it has changed since the last delivery, and if it has, then type in the new wholesale price in pence, excluding VAT, followed by the Enter key. (Exclude VAT even if you are unregistered.)
\par Entry then moves to the Product price box. If this has changed, type in the new price in pence, followed by the Enter key. If a new price label is needed, press the function key, F10. (Note that the price label will be at the old price if the price has changed. Step through to the end to accept the entry and then scan the pack again before pressing F10.)
\par If you wish to maintain the margin after a price increase, type in the margin and press the Enter key to give a new price at the specified margin.\tab 
\par If the margin is out of range of the default department margin, a warning dialog will appear. The mouse can be used to go back to the Product price box if a change is needed. If not, pressing the Enter key again will enter the data into the database.
\par The Cancel button will cancel the current inputs but leave the screen active while the Quit button or the Escape key will return to the sales screen.
\par It is permissible to have a Number of cases value of zero. This allows the wholesale price to be updated without a delivery.
\par Pressing the Enter key will operate the OK button. The delivery is then entered into the delivery table and any changes made are updated.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_selectdelivery}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_selectdelivery}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 12.2.\tab Select delivery
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {deliveries}}}{\v{\xe {completed}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 When the menu function Tables>Deliveries is actioned, the first screen shown is Deliveries. This screen shows all of the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul deliveries\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  outstanding that have not been completed. The operator can select one of these and then click the OK button.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
