 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Delivery}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Delivery}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 12.3.\tab Delivery
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {'Completed'}}}{\v{\xe {delivery entry}}}{\v{\xe {Deliveries}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 The 'Delivery' screen appears after selecting a delivery in the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Deliveries\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen and pressing the details button. It shows a table of stock that has been delivered and then entered via the '\plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Delivery entry\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 ' screen. A running total of the total cost of items listed is shown, and the operator can enter the equivalent total from an invoice in the 'Invoice total' box. The same is true for tax. There is also a 'Completed' checkbox to show that the delivery has been fully dealt with. When the default OK button is clicked, these values are saved.
\par If wholesale prices are entered during delivery entry, these are shown as Invoice total when the screen is opened. There will be times when the true price is not known when the delivery is received, and the prices entered will be the previous price, the price calculated using the default margin, or zero. In the delivery screen, prices can be corrected and ultimately, the two sets of figures should tally. Remember to operate the OK (tick) button to save any changes.
\par Note that completed deliveries will no longer appear as a choice when \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul delivery entry\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  is attempted.
\par At the top of the screen are buttons that can change the retail and wholesale (pack) price of the selected delivery line by clicking the appropriate button and then making the change. This allows for the correction of entries in line with the invoice, when this is delivered at a later date.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 13.\tab Stock
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_addtostock}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_addtostock}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 13.1.\tab Add to stock
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {delivery}}}{\v{\xe {add to stock}}}{\v{\xe {product}}}{\v{\xe {barcode}}}{\v{\xe {wholesale}}}{\v{\xe {pack size}}}{\v{\xe {supplier}}}{\v{\xe {alpha lookup}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The Add to Stock screen is used to add products to the system where there is no purchase, such as free stock from visiting reps or replacement for faulty stock. 
\par This screen should never be used for general stock entry; instead use the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Delivery\plain\f4\fs24  screen, so that stock levels are checked, wholesale price, pack size and supplier are recorded.
\par The Add to stock screen is activated from the menu item '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Stock |Add to stock\plain\f4\fs24 '. Just scan or type in the bar code, or begin typing the name of the product and use the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul alpha lookup\plain\f4\fs24  procedure.
\par If the product is recognised, the product description will appear and the focus moves to the Quantity box. Type in the quantity, press Enter to move to the OK button and then press Enter again to accept. The stock levels will be amended. The screen can also be used to reduce the stock level by typing in a negative (minus) number. We have used this facility on occasion to transfer stock from multi-packs to single items. If the product is not recognised the focus returns to the Product ID' box and the system issues a long beep.
\par The screen is closed by pressing the Cancel button or by using the Escape key.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_startingstock}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_startingstock}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 13.2.\tab Starting stock
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {starting stock}}}{\v{\xe {1000 code}}}{\v{\xe {new product}}}{\v{\xe {hot key}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 This screen is activated from the menu with '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Stock |Starting stock\plain\f4\fs24 '.
\par Type or scan a new product code (twice to ensure no miss-scans) and the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul New Product\plain\f4\fs24 ' screen will appear. 
\par Pressing the 10000 Code button will create an unused \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul 10000 code\plain\f4\fs24 , including the initial 10000.
\par Entering a single letter will create a new product for a \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul hot key\plain\f4\fs24 . Pressing the Quit button with the mouse or pressing the Escape key returns to the sales screen.
\par The Starting stock screen can be used for the initial entry of stock when you are starting out, but it should not be used generally; instead use the delivery screen.
\par When a new product is created, it will be assigned default Pack and PackSupplier records based on the defaults set in the department chosen.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_tempstock}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_tempstock}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 13.3.\tab Default stock
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {default}}}{\v{\xe {temp}}}{\v{\xe {unlink}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 All products should be assigned to a department other than the default department. If any have been left assigned to the default department, or 'unlinked' in the Propduct screen, they can be correctly assigned using default stock.
\par Select the menu item Stock>Default stock.
\par If there are any stock items assigned to the default department, the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul New Product\plain\f4\fs24 ' screen will appear. The details for each product can be entered or modified followed by clicking the 'OK' button. Default products are examined in reverse order of creation, and each product should be defined before moveing on to the next. Items on the a,b and c keys are excluded.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_linkproducts}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_linkproducts}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 13.4.\tab Link products
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 This screen allows you to link products simply. First select a department, then from the list of products shown, select the first and then click the Select button. Then click the second product and then click the second Select  button. Finally click the Link button.
\par Then the Link SKUs screen appears. When you link two products, there is one quantity for both; the default is to sum the two separate quantities. The figure may be changed if required. No loss will be recorded in this case.
\par Finally click the Link to first (or second) button. Both products will be linked to the SKU of the first (or second). Normally, choose the lower SKU number.
\par A single department may show too many different products to clearly see product that should be linked: the Alpha box allows a smart search, similar to the alpha lookup function, to reduce the number of products shown. For instance, if we start with the tobacco department, typing the first two or three letters of Lambert & Butler will reduce the selection to a handful of product. \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 14.\tab Stocktaking
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_STOCKTAKING}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_STOCKTAKING}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 14.1.\tab Stocktaking
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {stocktaking}}}{\v{\xe {theft}}}{\v{\xe {staff theft}}}{\v{\xe {record}}}{\v{\xe {deliveries}}}{\v{\xe {recording errors}}}{\v{\xe {rolling}}}{\v{\xe {date stamped}}}{\v{\xe {stock checks}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Accurate stocktaking is the most important element of a computerised stock control system. Scanning at the point of sale will eliminate almost all errors in stock purchased by customers but errors can be introduced by a number of other factors.
\par \pard\li360\fi-360\tx360{\*\pn\pnlvlblt\pnf1\pnindent360{\pntxtb\'b7}}\plain\f4\fs24 {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Customer theft \endash  the most obvious source of errors
\par {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Staff theft \endash  often larger than customer theft
\par {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Failure to record stock when delivered
\par {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Recording stock deliveries more than once, or miss-keying the number of packs
\par {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Errors in pack sizes recorded
\par {\pntext\f1\'b7\tab}Miss-counts or recording errors during a stock-take
\par \pard\plain\f4\fs24 While theft levels are important information when running a shop, errors due to other effects can often disguise true theft levels. Errors in stock levels will also result in unnecessary out-of-stocks and over-ordering. The more effective the ordering system is at minimising the total stock levels, the more damaging stock level errors will be.
\par Consider the effect of the theft of say three bars of chocolate. Until the stock level is checked and corrected, the chocolate bars may never be ordered again.
\par The same problem can arise with routine stock-takes. Say there has just been a delivery of the same chocolate bars, and there are now 50 bars on the shelf. With a number this large it is fairly easy to make a mistake. Three under, and you will end up in the same situation and be convinced that there is a theft problem.
\par Data entry is also a problem. Extra key presses such as typing 77 instead of 7 can lead to significant errors. Entering a sheet of stock-take figures can lead to whole pages of errors when a single row is missed out.
\par The stocktaking methods used here have been evolved to reduce all these errors to a minimum.
\par First, all stock checks are date stamped. This allows for stocktaking on a rolling basis.
\par Second, stocktaking can be confined to items with a low stock count \endash  less than ten items. This allows for rapid stocktaking and few errors in counts. This does mean that if this method is used exclusively, slow moving stock with high counts may never be counted, but errors in slow moving stock do not impact on profitability to the same degree.
\par Third, a stock-take of lines ordered is routinely done. These tend to be mostly low numbers, and this eliminates over-ordering due to errors caused by not entering stock when delivered.
\par The result of these strategies is that most stock is stock-checked every month without much effort. Fast moving stock will be counted much more often.
\par The Stocktaking by Department>All screen can be activated by using the Alt-s combination.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_STOCKTAKE}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_STOCKTAKE}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 14.2.\tab Stock take
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {stock take}}}{\v{\xe {stock}}}{\v{\xe {product}}}{\v{\xe {quantity}}}{\v{\xe {date}}}{\v{\xe {shortage}}}{\v{\xe {loss}}}{\v{\xe {encoded}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The stock take screen is shown when the menu selection Stock|Stock take|All is selected. There are also options for stock taking a single product, a department, all stock of a single supplier, all stock with a zero, or with a negative level. There is also an option to stock take items with a quantity of less than 10. This option is sometimes useful as it avoids counting large numbers, as mentioned in the previous help page.
\par The Stock take screen shows a table of 26 entries with columns headed SKU (Stock Keeping Unit), Product, Quantity and Date.
\par The SKU and Product columns show the SKU ID and linked product description. Remember that when multiple products are linked by a common stock entry, that only one count is maintained. The product description shown is the one with the last recorded delivery.
\par The Quantity column shows the recorded stock quantity. Clicking on this column with the left-hand mouse button will open this quantity for editing. Simply over-type the new value and then press the Enter key. Any downward change in stock level will be recorded in the sales table as a positive \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul loss\plain\f4\fs24 . 
\par The Date column, which shows the date of the last stock take, will then change to the current date, and the item will cease to be displayed. 
\par When all the stock levels have been checked, clicking the All Checked button will change all of the dates to the current date and close the screen.
\par The Print button (or Alt P) prints the visible table on the default printer whereas the function key F10 will print to a receipt printer if fitted. The screen is closed after printing. Quit or escape close the screen in other cases.
\par Note that products can only appear in the stock take screen if the date they were last checked is before today's date. New products that have only been created today will not appear unless the quantity was never changed from the default of zero. Also \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul price encoded\plain\f4\fs24  and \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul weight encoded\plain\f4\fs24  products are excluded completely.
\par For each option, you can select either Default or All; Default will show a screen of 26 items, All will show a screen with all items, using scroll bars if needed. Use default for preference.
\par 
\par To do a routine stocktake:
\par 1  Use Default setting of the stocktake screen
\par 2  Press Print key to get a list of stock
\par 3  Check each quantity matches or write down correct quantity next to quantity
\par 4  Call up same stocktake screen - it will show same products
\par 5  Correct any wrong figures by typing into the quantity column and pressing Enter. The line will disappear.
\par 6  When all corrections have been made, press the All checked button. The scree will close
\par 7  Calling up the same screen again will show a different set of products, until they have all been checked.
\par Notes:
\par Stock level can change whilst counting is taking place, due to sales - this is why the default is a better choice than all - it limits the time taken. (default shows just 22 products)
\par Arrow keys can be used to navigate.
\par Any corrections will appear as Losses in the sales table.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_STOCKVALUE}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_STOCKVALUE}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 14.3.\tab Stock value
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {other's}}}{\v{\xe {value}}}{\v{\xe {our stock}}}{\v{\xe {other's stock}}}{\v{\xe {wholesale}}}{\v{\xe {VAT}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 This screen is activated by the menu command '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Stock |Stock value |All\plain\f4\fs24 '. There are two buttons \endash  Our stock and Other's stock. Clicking Our stock with the mouse will start the calculation of the total stock value at wholesale price without VAT. The displayed table can be used to identify gross errors - find which department is affected and then use the menu option '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Stock |Stock value |Department\plain\f4\fs24 ' to see which individual stock item is causing problems. The Other's stock button performs the same calculation on stock which is still owned by a supplier.
\par Cells in the displayed table may be selected with the mouse and then copied to the clipboard by the labeled button. They may then be pasted into a spreadsheet program such as Excel got further analysis or display.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 15.\tab Reports
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_takings}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_takings}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 15.1.\tab Takings
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {takings report}}}{\v{\xe {reports}}}{\v{\xe {takings}}}{\v{\xe {daily}}}{\v{\xe {weekly}}}{\v{\xe {monthly}}}{\v{\xe {yearly}}}{\v{\xe {Excel}}}{\v{\xe {graph}}}{\v{\xe {spreadsheet}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Under the menu heading Reports are a number of different reports. The first of these is Takings. This screen allows for a calculation of takings by daily, weekly, monthly or yearly periods.
\par To use it simply, choose the period, (daily, weekly, monthly or yearly) by clicking on the appropriate tab, then set the start date by clicking on the down arrow of the Start date box. This will reveal a small monthly calendar. A small left pointing arrow can be clicked to reach earlier months. By default, the date is set to the current day for the daily page, the current week starting on a Sunday for the weekly page, the current month starting on the first day for the monthly page and the current year starting on the first of January.
\par Then choose a department by clicking on the down arrow of the Department box and selecting a department. This allows calculation of the trade for any specific department to be determined. The next drop down box allows for the selection of a specific product within the department, for detailed analysis. Calculations can be done retrospectively for multiple periods, such as each month for the past year.
\par Then click on the Calculate button. The takings for the day, week, month or year will be calculated and displayed. When earlier dates are selected, more than one row of results will appear.
\par When completed, as shown by the cursor reverting from an hourglass to a pointer, the results can be printed, by clicking the Print button. 
\par Sometimes the calculations are quite lengthy but even if incomplete, the screen can always be cancelled by clicking the Cancel button or by pressing the Escape key.
\par All results exclude VAT except for the Sales column, which is gross. The Profit column is based on the current purchase price so will not be truly accurate if historical figures are calculated. Own use sales are based at wholesale purchase price. Returns and Losses refer to the selected department only. Agency takings are excluded from all takings figures. The columns for returns, wastes, etc. refer only to a selected department and not all sales.
\par If your interest is in the performance of a particular product or department over time, then using the desired interval, choose the page: monthly sale are generally the most useful. Then choose a starting date, and click the Calculate button. When the calculations are completed, use the mouse to select the figures of interest by clicking and dragging the mouse. 
\par The selected figures will be highlighted in blue with standard colouring. Click on the copy button and then open up your favourite spread sheet program. I have used Excel here. Select a starting point and then paste the figures into the spread sheet by pressing Control-V' key combination (or clicking the paste icon). A few steps more and the results can be converted into a graph of sales. Here showing an uncharacteristic rise.\plain\f5\fs24  \plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par 
\par \plain\f5\fs24\cf0\b Cashing up\plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 This has now been transferred to the Cashing up screen on the reports menu.\plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Salesby}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Salesby}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 15.2.\tab Sales by
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Clicking on this option reveals four further options: sales by department, operator, quantity and value. Clicking on any of these leads to the same screen. An addition set of reports include wastes, losses, returns, charges, received on account and own use. Operation of each is fairly self-explanatory - just set a start date and an end date and then click OK. A report of all sales in the selected period is produced after a delay. 
\par The reports on discounts or priced over will only show the sales in which one or more products have been discounted or priced over, as this is the only information saved. If it is desired to know which item was affected, it will be necessary to examine the sales record and determine which prices have been altered from normal.
\par A print button is provided that will print out an image of the screen on the default printer. There is also a copy button that will appear after the ok button has been clicked. This will copy the whole of the displayed results to the clipboard. These values can then be pasted into a spreadsheet for subsequent analysis.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_salesReports}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_salesReports}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 15.3.\tab Sales reports
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {own use}}}{\v{\xe {not completed}}}{\v{\xe {agency}}}{\v{\xe {losses}}}{\v{\xe {wastes}}}{\v{\xe {returns}}}{\v{\xe {department}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 When the Reports heading on the menu bar is clicked with the mouse, a number of options are revealed.
\par '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Takings\plain\f4\fs24 ' and '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Cash up\plain\f4\fs24 ' are detailed elsewhere.
\par Own use shows all sales that have been charged to own use.
\par Agency show individual agency transactions.
\par Losses, Wastes and Returns show products that have been shown as lost on a stock count, or have been wasted or returned at the point of sale.
\par Selecting Department reveals a sub-menu that allows these same losses, wastes and returns to be restricted to just one department.
\par All of the results of these selections are shown in date and time order, with the most recent at the bottom of the screen. It can take some time to produce these results, so they should only be attempted during slack periods or after closing. They can be useful in tracking down errors when cashing up. Clicking the Cancel button or pressing the Escape key will close the Results screen.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 16.\tab Cashing up
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_thecashingupprocess}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_thecashingupprocess}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 16.1.\tab The cashing up process
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 At the end of each operator's shift, the money in the cash drawer needs to be checked. The standard process for this is for the operator to use the menu option 'Reports|Cash up'. A short printout is issued from the receipt printer and the cash drawer will open. This should be placed together with the cash for subsequent reconcilliation. This can either be in a separable cash tray, or in a bag or other suitable device.
\par Subsequently, the person responsible for cash should reconcile the cash amounts. They select the menu option 'Reports|Reconcile cashups' and select the cashup ID on the printout with the money from the list displayed. Then, after clicking the OK button, the money can be counted and the counts entered into the left hand column of boxes, as appropriate using the Tab key to step from box to box. The values can be typed in. When all of these amounts have been entered, click the 'Calculate' button.
\par The error in the cash amount is shown together with lists of 'Debits', 'Cheques', 'Coupons', 'Received on account' and 'Paid outs', and their totals. Check these all against the paperwork that should be with the cash. Any errors should be entered into the totals boxes for record. 
\par Finally click the 'Save' button. 
\par For the 'Float' - the cash put into the cash drawer at the start of a shift, there are two options. The first is to set the 'Float value' on the settings screen to some value in pence; so for a \'a325 float, set the value to 2,500. It is then expected that the float will be \'a325 every time the cashing up process is started. The second option is for the 'Float value' to be set to zero. When this is the case, at the start of a shift, the operator will be asked to enter the float value, in pence. Once this has been done, operators will not be asked again until 'Reports|Cash up' is activated. This is true even if the operators change during the day.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_cashup}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_cashup}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 16.2.\tab Cashing up
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {cashing up}}}{\v{\xe {cash up}}}{\v{\xe {float}}}{\v{\xe {agency}}}{\v{\xe {takings}}}{\v{\xe {debit}}}{\v{\xe {cheque}}}{\v{\xe {coupon}}}{\v{\xe {backup}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f2\fs24 On selecting 'Reports|Cashing up', a display of key figures is shown since the last cashing up. These are the total Takings, Charges, Agency sales, and the totals for Coupons, Debits and Paid outs. In addition, the sum of accounts charged is shown. These figures will include any tax taken. In addition, the start and end date and time for the cashing up period (Starting from the last time and ending now), and the operator who performed the cashing up. On clicking OK, the program closes down. To reconcile the takings, the cash, debits,coupons and Paid outs in the till should equal to the Takings figure less the Charges plus any Agency sales.  The figure for the takings for accounting purposes is taken from '\plain\f2\fs24\cf2\ul Reports|Takings\plain\f2\fs24 ' for the given period. The takings are counted and reconciled using the \plain\f2\fs24\cf2\ul Cashup reconcilliation\plain\f2\fs24  screen.
\par \plain\f5\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f2\fs16 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_cashupreconcilliation}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_cashupreconcilliation}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 16.3.\tab Cashup reconcilliation
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Selecting 'Reports|Cashup reconcilliation' will bring up a  list of the ID's of 'Cashups' that have not been reconciled. Choose one and then click OK, to bring up the cashup reconcilliation screen for that cashup.
\par Here you can start by reconciling the 'debits', 'cheques', 'coupons', 'received on accounts' and 'paid outs' against the paper record. Any unresolved discrepancy can be entered in the 'total' boxes below the columns.
\par Then, starting with \'a350 notes (subject to currency of course), enter the count of each note or coin in the appropriate  location, tabbing from space to space. (Shift Tab will take you back one step) When you have entered the figures for all of the cash in the cash drawer, click on the Calculate button. Then click on the 'Calculate float' button. 
\par The net error is shown on the screen. The error will be positive if the is too much cash in the cash drawer. The paper document associated with debits, cheques, etc should then be reconciled. If for any of these, reconcilliation proves impossible, the total figure for the item should be altered, so that at least the error is recorded.
\par When complete, click the 'Save' button to save the reconciled cashup in the database. reconciled cashups can be viewed later from the Tables menu. (Still to be implemented)
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_reconciledcashups}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_reconciledcashups}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 16.4.\tab Reconciled cashups
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 The option 'Tables|Reconciled cashups' makes it possible to return to past cashups, but not to alter them. When activated, only reconciled cashups with recorded errors are show, but if you uncheck a the 'In error' checkbox, all previous reconciled cashups can be seen.
\par By clicking any line in the display and then clicking the 'Details' button, you can see all further details that were recorded.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_cashupselect}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_cashupselect}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 16.5.\tab Cashup select
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 This simple dialog presents a list of unreconciled cashups, listing the ID, the till number and the date cashed up. Select the one you want with the mouse and then press the OK button or press Enter.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 17.\tab New records
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_newpack}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_newpack}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 17.1.\tab New pack record
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {new pack}}}{\v{\xe {new product}}}{\v{\xe {delivery }}}{\v{\xe {short codes}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Fill in the details of the pack. A Product ID, such as a bar code, can be scanned or typed in or a search of the Products database by typing in the first few letters selecting a product with the mouse. If the product is not recognised then the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul New Product\plain\f4\fs24 ' screen will appear.
\par The Pack code on the first screen is the code entered in the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Delivery screen\plain\f4\fs24 ' except in the case of short codes where there is a strong chance that two manufacturers will use the same code. In this case, the code will be preceded by the Supplier ID followed by a '+' symbol. This creates a unique extended code for the pack; however, there is never any need to enter this extended code \endash  just stick to the short code on entry, and the extra characters will be added by the system. Pack codes are not necessarily restricted to numbers, to allow supplier stock codes to be used. These can normally be read from the invoice.
\par When the OK button is clicked, or the Enter key pressed, the new \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul PackSupplier\plain\f4\fs24  form is shown.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_newpacksupplier}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_newpacksupplier}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 17.2.\tab New pack supplier
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {pack}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f5\fs24\cf0 The new Pack Supplier Dialog is generated by the delivery screen when a new record must be created. This happens when a pack is new for the supplier selected. Only the price in pence has to be filled in. Press the Enter key to accept the entry or the Escape key to dismiss the screen without entry.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_newproduct}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_newproduct}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 17.3.\tab New product record
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {new product}}}{\v{\xe {sales}}}{\v{\xe {new pack}}}{\v{\xe {product ID}}}{\v{\xe {description}}}{\v{\xe {alpha lookup}}}{\v{\xe {KitKat}}}{\v{\xe {price}}}{\v{\xe {VAT}}}{\v{\xe {temporary product}}}{\v{\xe {Delivery entry}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The New Product screen will appear if an attempt to sell an unknown product is made using the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Delivery entry\plain\f4\fs24  screen; or if an unknown product is placed in a \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul New Pack\plain\f4\fs24  Screen; or if the menu item '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Stock |Starting stock\plain\f4\fs24 ' is activated and a new product code is scanned in.
\par The screen will appear with the Product ID' filled in and the focus on the Description box. Type in a convenient description. Remember that the description is used in the Alpha lookup so the third character should be a letter or a space and not a number. After pressing the Enter key, the focus moves to the Department drop down box and the first character of each word in the description is capitalised so there is generally no need to enter capitals. Select the desired department using the mouse or the up/down arrow keys. After pressing the Enter key, pressing the down arrow on the Stock box will reveal an alphabetically ordered list of products. If the new product is to be linked to one of these, select it with the mouse. Products are linked if a common count is to be maintained. For instance, a price marked KitKat bar would be linked to an unmarked KitKat bar. If it is a totally new product, leave this box blank. Then press the Enter key and the focus will move to the Price box. Enter the price in pence followed by the Enter key.
\par The focus moves to the Priced check box. This indicates that, when ticked, that the product is price marked. It is ticked by left clicking with the mouse, or by pressing the space bar
\par The box labeled Per is intended for a column \'a3xx.xx per 'metre' or similar.
\par If you continue to press the Enter key without filling in a department, the product is created as a temporary product and the rest of the information can be added later with the Starting stock screen.
\par If possible, it is better to fill in the details, as this will ensure the correct VAT treatment and stock level adjustment when the product is sold. 
\par When the Enter key is pressed with the Stock drop-down box blank, the '\plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul New Stock Screen\plain\f4\fs24 ' will appear.
\par Pressing the Quit button or pressing the Escape key will return to the previous screen without saving any entries.
\par There is occasional confusion with price \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul encoded products\plain\f4\fs24  - some products appear to have codes that might otherwise be price encoded. Products that are encoded can be set to encoded by price or encoded by weight but those that are neither can be left as 'not encoded. The encoded state is set prior to displaying the New product screen. The codes for encoded product are not entirely standard, having been set for internal use only. The 8th bit should be a parity bit but some implementations make this bit significant for product identification. In this case, the Parity checkbox should be unchecked for encoded products.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_newsku}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_newsku}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 17.4.\tab New stock
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {stock}}}{\v{\xe {quantity}}}{\v{\xe {default supplier}}}{\v{\xe {default case size}}}{\v{\xe {department}}}{\v{\xe {VAT rate}}}{\v{\xe {excluded from stock take}}}{\v{\xe {included in stock take}}}{\v{\xe {other peoples stock}}}{\v{\xe {video}}}{\v{\xe {stopped}}}{\v{\xe {new stock}}}{\v{\xe {description}}}{\v{\xe {VAT}}}{\v{\xe {excluded}}}{\v{\xe {included}}}{\v{\xe {default}}}{\v{\xe {photocopies}}}{\v{\xe {linked}}}{\v{\xe {stock minimum}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The Stock quantity box would normally be left at zero for new stock if this dialog has been generated by a stock entry procedure. If it has been generated from the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul sales screen\plain\f4\fs24  or from \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul starting stock\plain\f4\fs24  entry, the value can be filled in.
\par Stock minimum is normally set to zero. A higher value should ensure that the stock level should never fall below that value.
\par The Default case size and Default supplier are used to enable ordering of stock that did not originally arrive in a case, such as where a rep leaves a few bars of a new line of chocolate. Filling these in will ensure that they will be re-ordered when the stock is gone.
\par The Department is self-explanatory; after selection, the Vat rate will be set to the default for the department. If this is not correct, then change it as required. A separate Vat rate has been set up for video rental (or services), even though these incur standard rate in the UK.
\par The next drop down box allows a choice between four options; Excluded from stock take, Included in stock take (the default), Other peoples stock, and Videos. Most stock is of course included in any stock take. The option Other peoples stock, allows for a separate value to be calculated for stock that is put into the shop but not paid for until sold. Videos for rent have to be treated separately, as a rental does not decrease the stock level. Certain other items have to be excluded from any stock take. One example would be photocopies.
\par Move between fields using the Tab key and press the Enter key to accept all of the values entered. Escape will close the screen without accepting any values.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_supplier}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_supplier}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 17.5.\tab Supplier
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {Suppliers}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The supplier screen is displayed from th \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Suppliers\plain\f4\fs24  screen by clicking the 'New' button or by selecting a supplier and clicking 'Details'. The Default supplier cannot be modified. The box labeled Weeks credit is straightforward. It is used in the calculation of yield. Yield is a calculation of return on money invested, and clearly, the only money invested that is of concern to retailers is their own money.
\par The box labeled Days to next delivery is the number of days between successive deliveries. If a supplier delivers just once a week, the entry will be 7. If deliveries are more than once a week, leave this entry blank.
\par The box labeled Days spare stock is set to indicate just how much stock will be sitting on the shelf just prior to the next delivery. A figure of one is a practical minimum, because of the variation in buying patterns of customers. Higher values can be of use when suppliers make infrequent deliveries. A low figure can only be tolerated with accurate stock level figures. Lack of diligence in stocktaking can result in products never being ordered.
\par The final entries are a row of check boxes labeled to represent the days of the week on which deliveries are made. For milk deliveries on six days a week, Monday to Saturday, simply click on all but the first button.
\par Note that by setting up the entries correctly, the ordering process is almost automatic but you may need to modify the order parameters if there is a break in the normal routine of deliveries, say for a Bank Holiday.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
\page \par \pard\plain \s1\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs36 18.\tab Tables
\par\keepn
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_deliveries}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_deliveries}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.1.\tab Deliveries
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {deliveries}}}{\v{\xe {'Delivery'}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 This screen available from the Tables menu, shows all \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul deliveries\plain\f3\fs20\cf0  \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 starting with the most recent. Selecting on and clicking the default 'Details' button will show the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul 'Delivery'\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen with more detail. \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Delivery}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Delivery}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.2.\tab Delivery
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {'Completed'}}}{\v{\xe {delivery entry}}}{\v{\xe {Deliveries}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 The 'Delivery' screen appears after selecting a delivery in the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Deliveries\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen and pressing the details button. It shows a table of stock that has been delivered and then entered via the '\plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Delivery entry\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 ' screen. A running total of the total cost of items listed is shown, and the operator can enter the equivalent total from an invoice in the 'Invoice total' box. The same is true for tax. There is also a 'Completed' checkbox to show that the delivery has been fully dealt with. When the default OK button is clicked, these values are saved.
\par If wholesale prices are entered during delivery entry, these are shown as Invoice total when the screen is opened. There will be times when the true price is not known when the delivery is received, and the prices entered will be the previous price, the price calculated using the default margin, or zero. In the delivery screen, prices can be corrected and ultimately, the two sets of figures should tally. Remember to operate the OK (tick) button to save any changes.
\par Note that completed deliveries will no longer appear as a choice when \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul delivery entry\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  is attempted.
\par At the top of the screen are buttons that can change the retail and wholesale (pack) price of the selected delivery line by clicking the appropriate button and then making the change. This allows for the correction of entries in line with the invoice, when this is delivered at a later date.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_department}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_department}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.3.\tab Department
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 The Department screen is displayed from Departments either by clicking the 'New' button or by selecting a department and clicking the 'Modify' button.
\par The first field is the department description, a field that is capitalised after stepping on with the Tab key. Next is a tax drop-down box. Choose the default tax for this department using the arrow keys. Tab to the next field and select the default supplier for goods in this department. The next field, 'Default margin', is the expected percentage on return (por) for this range of goods. The default minimum specifies a minimum stock level, but leave this as zero for best use of the system.
\par Restriction is either an age, say 18 for alcohol, or the letter P for pharmacist permission with UK law. Click the OK button to accept the new or changed department or use the Escape key to dismiss the screen.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_departments}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_departments}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.4.\tab Departments
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {department}}}{\v{\xe {Temp A}}}{\v{\xe {Temp B}}}{\v{\xe {agency}}}{\v{\xe {video}}}{\v{\xe {default}}}{\v{\xe {retail}}}{\v{\xe {wholesale}}}{\v{\xe {restricted}}}{\v{\xe {pharmacy}}}{\v{\xe {P+}}}{\v{\xe {18+}}}{\v{\xe {age restricted products}}}{\v{\xe {'Tracked'}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The department table is modified by selecting the menu item Tables|Departments with the mouse.
\par The empty database is provided with a default department. Fresh departments can be added to suit a wide variety of stores by clicking 'New'. The department Temp A' should not be deleted, as it is the default for non-coded items. The departments Agency and Video have special significance, and should not be changed, but may be deleted if not required. The descriptive field may be changed if required. Use the New button to create a new department with a unique ID, and then save it by clicking the OK button. The margin is the retail margin used to calculate a wholesale price, prior to recording a genuine wholesale price.
\par Products within a department that is restricted can be identified by characters in the Restriction field.  For age restricted products, enter the Restriction with the age such as "18" Two digits are allowed for the age, so if only one is required, make the second one a space. Another option is for pharmacy use. In the UK, some pharmacy products can only be sold with the pharmacists approval. These are indicated by the restriction " P". Restricted products will result in a request for pharmacist approval after a warning sound. Pressing the enter or y key is all that is required to continue with the sale. Pressing n for no will stop the sale of that item.
\par The third sort of restriction is \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul 'Tracked'\plain\f4\fs24  items, identified by the letter 'T' in the restriction field.
\par \tab 
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_hotkeys}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_hotkeys}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.5.\tab Hotkeys
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 A table of hotkeys in use is displayed by this menu selection. There is no new button but new hotkeys can be created by entering a letter in the 'Stock|Starting stock' screen.\plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 If you need to re-assign a hotkey to a different product, look at the details, and then #Unlink' the product. The hotkey will then appear in 'Stock|Temp stock' ready to be re-named or linked to another product.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_operator}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_operator}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.6.\tab Operator
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {operator}}}{\v{\xe {ID}}}{\v{\xe {privileges}}}{\v{\xe {managers}}}{\v{\xe {staff}}}{\v{\xe {takings}}}{\v{\xe {cashing up}}}{\v{\xe {trainee}}}{\v{\xe {locked}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 This screen is activated from the Tables|Operators menu item and then clicking New or Details. The authority ratings run from 0 to 5. 
\par 0. The operator has full privileges \endash  reserved for owners.
\par 1. The operator has almost the same privileges; for use by managers.
\par 2. Senior staff member with addition rights to input deliveries.
\par 3. Staff member with right to input deliveries.
\par 4. Trainee staff member. Not actively allowed  to complete sales, but the sales screen if functional for training.
\par 5. The till is locked to prevent unauthorised use.
\par The Print button is used to print out details, including a bar code using the default printer, suitable for laminating to make a staff pass.
\par Printed passes will have a preceding 1000037 so that the pass will be recognised by the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul sales screen\plain\f4\fs24 .
\par Once you have created an additional operator, and at least one of these has owner or manager status, you can change the authority of the Default operator to 6.
\par In addition, you can allow any operator additional permissions by ticking the appropriate check box.
\par In addition, each operator can have privaleges ascribed. This allows a shopkeeper to decide what activities each member of staff can perform on a case by case basis.
\par Managers can do all activities except modify Operators, without additional permission.\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_operators}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_operators}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.7.\tab Operators
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {'Product'}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 Display a list of all operators by clicking 'Tables|Operators'. Then you can click the 'New' button, or select an operator and then press the 'Details' button to display the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul 'Product'\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_packs}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_packs}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.8.\tab Packs
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {pack}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f8\fs24\cf0 The Packs screen show the basic details for pack codes. These records are created by the Delivery screen.
\par The box labeled Product allows the operator just see Packs that contain a desired product by entering or scanning a product code and pressing the tab button. The same can be done for an SKU. Remember that there may be more than one pack for each product. There are buttons to delete selected Packs. As a Pack cannot be deleted when there are linked Pack supplier records, there is a separate button to delete these records first.\plain\f9\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f8\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_packsuppliers}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_packsuppliers}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.9.\tab Pack supplier
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {pack supplier}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f5\fs24\cf0 The\plain\f10\fs24\cf0  Pack suppliers screen allows examination of Pack Supplier records. These records are created by the Delivery screen. Records can be deleted from the Packs screen if they are in error.
\par \plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f5\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_paidouts}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_paidouts}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.10.\tab Paid Outs
\par\keepn
\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 This displays a table of all paid outs. The paid outs are shown just for the till queried unless the till ID is zero in which case all paid outs are shown. Once started, set the start date and end date before clicking the OK button. The table can be sorted by clicking on any of the headers of the table. It is not possible to modify or delete entries.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs20\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_product}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_product}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.11.\tab Product
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {product}}}{\v{\xe {alpha lookup}}}{\v{\xe {starting stock}}}{\v{\xe {purchases}}}{\v{\xe {relational}}}{\v{\xe {price change}}}{\v{\xe {Settings}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 Product details are selected by left clicking the menu item Tables|Product with the mouse.
\par Locate the required product by typing or scanning the product's bar code or by typing in three or more letters of the product description and selecting with a mouse click, using the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Alpha lookup screen\plain\f4\fs24 . Details of the product can then be changed such as the product description and then clicking 'Update'.Clicking the Price change button can modify the selling price of a product. The details of the SKU that is linked to the product can also be modified by clicking on the 'SKU' button. These details are the entries below the line in the Product screen.
\par Pressing the Print key will print out a shelf edge label(TODO). Pressing the Print bar code button will print out an adhesive bar code label on an attached bar code printer selected in the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Settings\plain\f4\fs24  screen. 
\par A useful technique when a stock code has been wrongly assigned is to change the stock code to the code for a temporary product. This can be done easily by clicking the unlink button. A new stock code can then be assigned by using the \plain\f4\fs24\cf2\ul Starting stock\plain\f4\fs24  Screen.
\par It is not possible to delete a product, or modify a product ID once it has appeared is the sales table because of the relational integrity required. 
\par \plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_Products}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_Products}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.12.\tab Products
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {Product}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f3\fs24\cf0 The Products table is shown by selecting the menu item Table|Products.
\par A table of all products in the system is shown, in 'barcode' order. You can order them by description or by department by clicking on the appropriate column headers.
\par To find further details of a particular product, select the product with your mouse and then click the 'Details' button which will show the \plain\f3\fs24\cf2\ul Product\plain\f3\fs24\cf0  screen. 
\par If you select a product and then click  'Sell', or just press the Enter key, the product will be sold, just as though you scanned it.
\par Dismiss the screen by clicking the button with a small button marked x or by pressing the Escape key.
\par There is also a button  for printing a barcode on a dedicated barcode printer. This can be used with a multiple  selection if required.\plain\f5\fs20\cf0 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f3\fs24\cf0 
\par\pard
{\*\bkmkstart _topicpageref_sale}{\*\bkmkend _topicpageref_sale}\par \pard\plain \s2\keepn\tx1200\b\f6\fs32 18.13.\tab Sale
\par\keepn
{\v{\xe {sales}}}{\v{\xe {past sales}}}{\v{\xe {F10}}}\par \plain \keepn\f0\fs20 
\deflang2057\pard\plain\f4\fs24 The Sale screen, reached by the menu option Tables|Sale, allows a record of past sales to be examined. Forward and backward buttons allow stepping through sales in sequence. Alternatively, a particular sale can be selected in the 'Tables|Sales' menu selection, and then the Details buton clicked. Any sales record can be printed by pressing the Print button.
\par An operator cannot modify any of the details of past sales.
\par Individual sales records will show if a sale was cash, charged, own use, a return, a loss, a waste or received on account. 
\par Tracking information is displayed alongside the price when it exists.(TODO)\plain\f9\fs20 \
 \
 \
 \plain\f4\fs24 
\par\pard
